<PageShell
  title="Health Insurance for Seniors in New Zealand 2026 | Retirement Guide"
  description="Guide to health insurance for seniors retiring in New Zealand. Public healthcare access, Auckland hospitals, visa requirements, and coverage for expats 65+."
  headline="Health Insurance for Seniors in New Zealand"
  subheadline="New Zealand offers stunning landscapes, friendly culture, and English-speaking healthcare—but strict immigration requires significant assets or family ties."
  heroImage="/images/countries/new-zealand-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Compare Senior Plans →"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna-global"
>
  <h2 id="overview">Why Seniors Choose New Zealand</h2>
  <p>
    New Zealand offers breathtaking natural beauty, low crime rates, English-speaking culture, and a relaxed pace of life. For active retirees who love the outdoors—hiking, fishing, golf—New Zealand is hard to beat. The country is also known for its friendly, welcoming people.
  </p>

  <p>
    Auckland is the largest city with excellent hospitals. Wellington offers culture and government services. Christchurch is rebuilding with modern infrastructure. Queenstown and the South Island appeal to nature lovers. Smaller towns like Tauranga, Nelson, and Napier offer retirement-friendly climates.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Key Facts for Seniors</h3>
    <ul class="text-primary-800 space-y-2">
      <li><strong>Healthcare:</strong> Good quality; public system for residents</li>
      <li><strong>Language:</strong> English (Māori co-official)</li>
      <li><strong>Cost of Living:</strong> NZ$3,000-5,000/month; Auckland highest</li>
      <li><strong>Climate:</strong> Mild; north warmer, south cooler</li>
      <li><strong>Safety:</strong> Very safe; low crime rates</li>
      <li><strong>Time Zone:</strong> UTC+12/13 (distant from Europe/Americas)</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h2 id="healthcare-system">New Zealand's Healthcare System</h2>
  <p>
    New Zealand's public healthcare system is funded through taxation and provides free or subsidized care to residents and citizens. Public hospitals handle emergencies and serious conditions. GP visits cost NZ$50-70 for most adults, but are subsidized for those with Community Services Cards.
  </p>

  <p>
    ACC (Accident Compensation Corporation) covers all accidents for everyone in New Zealand, including visitors. This means accident-related care is free. However, illness-related care follows standard healthcare rules based on residency status.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-4 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-2">Wait Time Considerations</h3>
    <p class="text-amber-800 mb-0">
      Public hospital wait times for non-urgent procedures can be long—6-12 months for joint replacements, some surgeries. Many seniors add private insurance for faster specialist access and elective procedures.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="visa-requirements">Visa Options for Seniors</h2>
  <p>
    New Zealand has limited retirement visa options:
  </p>

  <h3>Parent Retirement Resident Visa</h3>
  <p>
    For parents of adult NZ citizens/residents. Requires investment of NZ$1 million for 4 years, plus NZ$500,000 settlement funds, plus NZ$60,000/year income. Very high threshold.
  </p>

  <h3>Investor Visa Categories</h3>
  <p>
    Investor 1: NZ$10 million for 3 years. Investor 2: NZ$3 million for 4 years plus business experience. Both can lead to residence but are primarily for active investors.
  </p>

  <h3>Parent Resident Visa</h3>
  <p>
    For parents of adult NZ citizen/resident children. Has a ballot system with limited places. No specific investment requirement but children must sponsor and meet income thresholds.
  </p>

  <h3>Visitor Visa</h3>
  <p>
    Up to 9 months (or 18 months with multiple entry) for visitors. No healthcare access beyond ACC (accidents). Requires comprehensive travel insurance.
  </p>

  <h2 id="insurance-requirements">Insurance Requirements</h2>
  <p>
    Insurance requirements vary significantly by visa:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Visitor visas:</strong> Comprehensive travel insurance required</li>
    <li><strong>Resident visas:</strong> Public healthcare access once granted</li>
    <li><strong>Work visas:</strong> Public healthcare access while employed</li>
    <li><strong>ACC coverage:</strong> All accidents covered for everyone in NZ</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-2">Insurance Strategy for New Zealand</h3>
    <p class="text-blue-800 mb-0">
      Non-residents need comprehensive international insurance. Residents get public healthcare but many add private insurance (Southern Cross is the main provider) for faster elective care. ACC handles all accidents regardless of status.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="recommended-providers">Recommended Insurance Providers</h2>
  <p>
    For seniors in New Zealand, these providers offer appropriate coverage:
  </p>

  <ComparisonTable columns={providerColumns} rows={providerRows} />

